Kalau menurut saya pentingkan people rather than proses ğŸ˜ğŸ‘ walaupun proses juga penting tapi lebih baik membangun great people dulu untuk great product
Saya pernah tanya pertanyaan yg mirip di group @ScrumJakarta\nIntinya, setidaknya harus paham juga coding.

Ini comment nya Pak Joshua Partogi\n\n"Agak challenging sih sejujurnya. Banyak tim Scrum yg bermasalah dgn technical debt. Saya observasi ketika SM tidak punya technical skill, SM nya tidak bisa mentoring dalam bersihin technical debt."

I think there are 2 angles
A. The sm works in a company that is in transition. They have a formal pm position. Managers call them sm now but still expect them to deliver things on time on budget According to upfront planning. This sm needs to make everyone aware that they need to change their thinking for her to be a good sm.
B. A pm becoming sm in an already agile organization. Then the sm has to unlearn behavior. For example stop pushing, start coaching. Stop making rigid planning, start communicating with people how to deliver most impact within each Sprint.

I'd rather have an empathic, social, structured sm than a technical one. It can help if sm understands coding but i believe the coaching and leadership competence is more important.

to add, for the first angle A, which is basically our org ğŸ˜Š i emphasize that like it or not SM's must become buffers between mgmt & their team. facilitate self-organization for the team, while in the other hand handle interactions with mgmt. esp. protect the team to be able to move on toward their agility

yes I agree > that 'relationship building' and 'balancing of different interests' is one of the core skills of a strong SM. Someone who is also willing to stand up to the bosses or the structure of the organization (which your 'girls' actually did in the meetup! :))

ini beberapa hal utama yang saya identify:
- Source code: Tentukan waktu merge request, pastikan lebih sering dari biasanya. Paling kurang 1 hari sekali, mungkin akhir hari. Jadi keesokannya sudah pasti ada di git pekerjaan hari sebelumnya. Sangat tabu meninggalkan code di lokal (PC kantor) yang tidak di-push ke git di akhir hari
- Akses: Pastikan akses untuk deploy, test, checking, maintain ke semua environment (VPN)
- Dokumentasi: Waktu yang baik untuk pindah ke solusi cloud. Pastikan bekerja di cloud, jangan di lokal (terutama PC kantor)
- Media komunikasi: Pastikan sudah setup Grup chat & Video conference

Selamat sore aci , saya mau bertanya mengenai pembuatan user stories pada praktek scrum.
Sedikit intro , tim saya sedang membuat sebuah applikasi dan applikasi tersebut dibangun menggunakan API pada setiap fungsi nya .

Untuk saat ini saya selaku PO selalu membuat 2 user stories untuk satu fitur . 1 untuk API dan yang satunya untuk tampilan UI beserta binding API didalamnya .

Apakah praktik tersebut benar ? atau seharusnya saya menggabungkan menjadi 1 stories saja karena benefit yang diterima user sama saja
mohon bantuan penjelasannya
terima kasih
Ikut bantu jawab ya, IMHO kalau terkait soal User Story sebaiknya dibuat sekecil mungkin supaya tim dev biasa secara self organize mengambil task task dari hasil user story yang kecil tersebut :)
ngak hanya kecil sih , jadi kriteria user story yang baik itu kan 3C + INVEST
Berarti benar benar tidak diperbolehkan ada ketergantungan antara user stories yah?
Kondisi saat ini yg saya alami untuk mendapatkan fitur di UI maka user stories API harus dikerjakan terlebih dahulu
Namun kondisi di UI ternyata suka unpredictable, sehingga harus ada penyesuaian di sisi API
IMHO sebenarnya boleh - boleh saja, karena 3C + INVEST ini kan hanya dijadikan patokan untuk user stories yang baik, kalau pada implementasinya masih ada depedensi ya sesuaikan saja mas

Great article. Do we have an example of a company in Indonesia that did it this way (as opposed to hiring a big consultancy to reorganize the whole structure big bang)?

there are plenty. But most I've seen over here are exactly as Denning describes: big consultancy with big re-org of structure first, then agile coaching second. Most of the big re-org structure are way too complex and way too hard to implement 'for real'. I believe in an iterative approach, but the problem is that re-org sells better to leaders, so that's how they all go about it (with very few exceptions) :)

Good morning, I have something to ask.
I know this is very basic, sorry for asking this.
Currently I'm writing a thesis about developing a system using the Scrum method for my undergraduate final project.
Previously I had never worked using Scrum. My question is, did the product backlog exist before the project began?
Or is the product backlog created the first time the Scrum Team meets?

Thankyou for the response.

Ideally, a product owner already maps out his vision, some high level roadmap and some initial backlog on epic or story level. He could do this alone, together with stakeholders or even together with the full scrum team (which will lead to a better understanding)

In my experience tha backlog is constructed before and during a project. 

This is all based on the information that the product owner and team has. I always aim to have a discovery session first with my po, sm, team and stakeholders before starting a project. This can be done in many format, sometimes my team and I would go to the customer's location to gain understanding of the product that we are building.

During the project, which consists of many sprints, customer feedback during the showcase can add or remove items from the backlog. 

The main thing is that the backlog items are created by the po in collaboration with the team and the customer.
Okay, thank you, Sir.

Thankyou, Sir.
One more question.
What kind of testing method usually used in Scrum?

In my case, I'm building web service with Scrum methodology. I was wondering is it ok to use unit testing in Scrum ?

Yes, absolutely OK.   Scrum doesn't say much about testing or code quality but unit testing is great development practice.   If you are interested in Agile approaches to testing/code quality read up about XP, Extreme Programming.   https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Extreme_programming
XP gave us user stories, pair programming, TDD, and eventually things like BDD and CI/CD can be seen as coming out of XP
you could build unit testing into your Definition of Done at a per unit of work level.  (DoD)

Honestly, my supervisors ask me for gathering some papers, or projects of web service development with Scrum.\n\nThey are not sure that there were people used Scrum to build web service. Because of the delivery process in scrum involving the product users, or at least product owner. They assumed that Web service could be something weird for non-technical users. Because of the representation of the resource is in JSON format.
ok yes I understand the issue, it's not customer facing so some elements of scrum dont apply strongly.  you can treat your internal stakeholders as customers in this context.
the product owner is the person who needs the Web service delivered and understands the business requirements
you dont have to use user story format - Scrum does not mandate this.
so your units of work could relate to elements of the JSON files that must be delivered
I highly recommend unit testing in any case
is there an element of uncertainty about the final product?  not fully defined yet?
if so, scrum is still a good framework to use

its entirely up to you. scrum itself does not dictate how you reach the quality of your increment and what testing method you are using for it. however, its not uncommon to use Test First Approaches like TDD or BDD in scrum. I usually recommend to start first with Test After so that the Dev teams get used with Mocks, Stubs and Fakes and are able to write proper unit test before moving to test first. in any case, with your sprint retrospective and highlighted improvement, sooner or later you move to more proper and automated testing with multiple test levels.

If you speak about an API you should have a look into Postman and how to write automated tests in Postman, i use it for BDD approaches too. It can describe fairly easy scenarios of json requests and responses so that a product owner together with the dev team can create easily a test specification that is used to verify the implementation before the work starts.
Thanks, Sir. I'll try to use Postman automated test.

Hi, Tech Enthusiast!

Suka wondering ga sih startup itu dapet revenue atau profitnya dari mana? Tau-tau dapet investment, jadi terkenal dan impactful banget, terus tau-tau jadi unicorn. 

Ternyata ga sesederhana itu. 

Banyak startup yang jatuh ke dalam jebakan passion atau hanya mengutamakan growth tanpa merencanakan bagaimana membangun bisnis yang sustainable. Padahal dalam membangun startup, selain menjadi disruptif dan memberikan impact, seorang founder juga harus memperhatikan bagaimana bisnis model mereka dibentuk, karena startup pada dasarnya tetaplah badan usaha yang tentunya membutuhkan aliran revenue agar tetap berjalan. Ditambah lagi saat ini sudah banyak perkembangan model bisnis yang bisa di explore, yang dapat memberikan revenue stream yang sehat.

Menjawab masalah di atas, kita bakal belajar kenapa memilih satu model bisnis yang viable atau layak sangat penting bagi kelangsungan sebuah startup, cara mengetahui apakah bisnis model kamu viable atau tidak, lalu harus bagaimana jika belum menemukan model bisnis yang cukup sehat untuk startup kamu?
